2026-06-24 17:49:38,341 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Actual-Close Inclusion Periods in FY2025\n\nSpaceX\'s fiscal year ends December 31, so FY2025 = January 1, 2025 through December 31, 2025 (365 days).\n\n### xAI (acquired February 2, 2026)\n- **0 months** of FY2025 on an actual-close basis.\n- The xAI merger closed on February 2, 2026 — after FY2025 had already ended. xAI was therefore never legally/economically consolidated within SpaceX during any portion of FY2025.\n\n### X Holdings (acquired March 28, 2025)\n- **Approximately 9.13 months** (≈ 9 months and 4 days) of FY2025 on an actual-close basis.\n- Calculation: March 28–31, 2025 (4 days of March) + April 1 through December 31, 2025 (9 full months) = 279 days out of 365 days in FY2025.\n- 279 / 365 × 12 ≈ **9.17 months** (equivalently, 9 full months + 4/31 of March ≈ 9.13 months).\n\n| Entity | Merger Effective Date | Actual-Close Months in FY2025 |\n|---|---|---|\n| xAI | February 2, 2026 | 0 months (closed after FYE 2025) |\n| X Holdings | March 28, 2025 | ~9.13 months (279 of 365 days) |\n\n## Analytical Challenge Created by Retrospective Recast Accounting\n\nBecause Elon Musk held a controlling financial interest in SpaceX, xAI, and X throughout the periods presented, the Mergers were accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control**. Under this accounting, the consolidated financial statements have been **retrospectively recast for all periods presented** to include the historical results of xAI and X at their historical carrying amounts (no new goodwill or intangibles recorded; intercompany transactions eliminated). The filing explicitly states this constitutes a **change in reporting entity** and that, as a result, **separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided**.\n\nThis creates several material analytical challenges:\n\n1. **Reported FY2025 figures do not reflect actual FY2025 economics.** The recast FY2025 income statement includes a full twelve months of xAI results, even though xAI was not actually consolidated until February 2, 2026 (zero actual-close months in FY2025). It also includes a full twelve months of X results, even though X was only consolidated from March 28, 2025 onward (~9.13 actual-close months). The "as-reported" FY2025 therefore overstates the actual combined economic activity that occurred under common ownership during that year.\n\n2. **No standalone SpaceX baseline exists.** Because every historical period is recast to include xAI and X, there is no period in the filing that reflects SpaceX on a standalone basis. An analyst cannot isolate SpaceX\'s organic launch/services business performance from the contributions of the AI and social-media businesses.\n\n3. **Year-over-year growth comparisons are distorted.** All comparative periods (FY2023, FY2024, FY2025) are presented on the same recast combined basis. Apparent growth or margin trends reflect the combined entity\'s economics rather than the organic trajectory of any single business, and the timing of when each entity\'s results were actually realized inside SpaceX is obscured.\n\n4. **Inability to assess actual contribution during genuine consolidation periods.** Because xAI is shown for all of FY2025 despite not closing until 2026, and X is shown for all of FY2025 despite closing only in late March 2025, the face of the financials cannot be used to determine what SpaceX\'s actual consolidated results were during the periods these entities were genuinely part of the reporting group. Related-party transactions that occurred pre-merger (e.g., between SpaceX and X, or SpaceX and xAI) have been eliminated, further blurring the boundary between pre- and post-combination activity.\n\n5. **Pro-forma-style presentation presented as "actual" history.** The recast presentation looks like a combined pro forma view but is presented as if it were actual historical results, which can mislead readers into treating the combined entity as having always existed in its current form. The economic substance — that these were separate Musk-controlled entities transacting at arm\'s length until the respective merger dates — is not visible in the reported numbers.\n\nIn short, retrospective common-control recasting means the FY2025 financials present a full-year combined xAI + X + SpaceX entity that, on an actual-close basis, never existed during FY2025: xAI contributed zero actual-close months and X contributed only ~9.13 months, yet both appear as if consolidated for the entire year. This makes it impossible to derive standalone SpaceX performance, true year-over-year organic growth, or the actual incremental contribution of each acquired business from the face of the recast financial statements alone.\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX Form S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) — Mergers and common-control retrospective recast accounting disclosures; consolidated financial statement periods presented"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
